  "prompt": "How much does it cost to register a trademark in the U.S.?",
  "response": "The cost to register a trademark in the United States can vary depending on several factors, including the type of application and how you file it. As of my last update, here are some general guidelines:\n\n1. **Application Fees**: The United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) offers two primary types of applications:\n   - **TEAS Plus**: This option requires the applicant to meet a number of requirements, including selecting goods/services from the USPTO's ID Manual. The filing fee is typically $250 per class of goods or services.\n   - **TEAS Standard**: This option is more flexible but has fewer requirements. The filing fee is typically $350 per class of goods or services.\n\n2. **Attorney Fees**: If you hire an attorney to help with the application process, you'll need to budget for those fees as well. Attorney fees can range from a few hundred to several thousand dollars, depending on the complexity of the registration.\n\n3. **Additional Costs**: There may be additional costs, such as submitting additional specimens or responses to office actions if the application encounters issues.\n\nThese fees are subject to change, so I recommend checking the USPTO's official website or consulting with a legal professional for the most current information.",
